Principal Component Analysis

Dataset water.sand.all.red.scaled

This dataset contains 151 individuals and 8 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs does not detect any outlier.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 76.82% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 76.82% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is high and thus the first plane represents an important part of the data variability. This value is strongly greater than the reference value that equals 38.96%, the variability explained by this plane is thus highly significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 839 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it is probably not useful to interpret the next dimensions.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA The first factor is major: it expresses itself 62.93% of the data variability. Note that in such a case, the variability related to the other components might be meaningless, despite of a high percentage.

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 1 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (62.93% against 21.3%). This observation suggests that only this axis is carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

3. Description of the dimension 1

Figure 3.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e.which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

##      station 
## 3.495953e-05

There only is one possible qualitative variable to illustrate the distance between individuals : station.

Figure 3.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction. The individuals are coloured after their category for the variable station.

Figure 3.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 3.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 58, 8, 33, 59, 15, 7, 9, 57, 109 and 83 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis (to the left of the graph).

The group in which the individuals 59, 15, 9 and 57 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable chl_a.
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The group in which the individuals 58, 8, 33, 7, 109 and 83 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables NO3, PO4, NH4, Ntotal, seston and chl_a (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The group 3 (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable secchi.
  • low values for the variables chl_a, seston, Ntotal, NH4, NO3 and PO4 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

4. Classification

Figure 4 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals sharing :

  • high values for the variable secchi.
  • low values for the variables chl_a, seston, NH4, Ntotal, NO3 and PO4 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 9, 15, 57 and 59. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables chl_a and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 7, 8, 33, 58, 83 and 109. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables PO4, NO3, Ntotal, NH4, seston and chl_a (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable secchi.
